--- In cantera@yahoogroups.com, David Goodwin &lt;dgoodwin@c...&gt; wrote:
&gt; When you call IdealGasMix, you should specify two arguments:  the 
file 
&gt; name (which may be either a .cti or .xml file), and the id tag of 
the 
&gt; phase within the file that you want to use.  For example, file 
&gt; gri30.cti (or gri30.xml) contains three phase definitions: &quot;gri30&quot; 
&gt; implements GRI-3.0 with no transport properties, &quot;gri30_mix&quot; uses 
&gt; mixture-averaged transport properties, and &quot;gri30_multi&quot; uses 
&gt; multicomponent ones.  From Python, Cantera builds the first phase 
it 
&gt; finds in the file if the id tag is not specified, which in this 
case 
&gt; would be &quot;gri30&quot; with no transport properties.  Currently, the C++ 
code 
&gt; does not do this - you have to specify an id tag.
&gt; 
&gt; But it probably should behave like it does in Python, and it is an 
easy 
&gt; fix to get this behavior.  In file Cantera/src/importCTML.cpp, find 
&gt; function &#39;buildSolutionFromXML&#39;. Replace the first line in the try 
&gt; block:
&gt; 
&gt;             x = get_XML_Node(string(&quot;#&quot;)+id, &root);
&gt; 
&gt; with this line:
&gt; 
&gt;              x = get_XML_NameID(nm, string(&quot;#&quot;)+id, &root);
&gt; 
&gt; Save the file, and rebuild and install Cantera. Now your program 
should 
&gt; work.
&gt; 
&gt; By the way, if you use the &#39;ctnew&#39; utility to create a Makefile for 
&gt; your application, the include statements in your program do not 
work.  
&gt; I changed the statements
&gt; 
&gt; #include &quot;Cantera.h&quot;
&gt; #include &quot;IdealGasMix.h&quot;
&gt; 
&gt; to
&gt; 
&gt; #include &lt;cantera/Cantera.h&gt;
&gt; #include &lt;cantera/IdealGasMix.h&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; and it compiled and ran.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Dave
